WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:32.300
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:32.417 --> 00:00:34.377
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:37.340
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:37.486 --> 00:00:39.966
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:40.150 --> 00:00:41.990
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:00:47.540 --> 00:00:53.420
We have to mention that as well.
You, Federer, and Nadal. -Yes.

00:00:54.420 --> 00:01:00.260
Three great giants.
Pushing each other forward, but...

00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:05.740
Not only in Serbia
and not only your fans, but...

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:12.740
I think at the beginning, that relationship
was quite-I’d even say-quite toxic.

00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:18.780
Not so much from Nadal's side,
but more from Federer’s and the media’s.

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:22.100
You mentioned that recently.

00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:27.740
They simply didn’t want to
include you in that perfect story.

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:34.620
You were like an unwanted child,
like Yoko Ono in the Beatles. -Yes.

00:01:35.046 --> 00:01:37.846
Did you feel that at the time?
-How could I not.

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:41.213
And did it frustrate you?
-Honestly, it did.

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:43.140
I can’t say it didn’t.

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:54.020
I’m a man with many flaws.
I’ve made a lot of mistakes,

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:57.500
but I’ve always tried
to live through the heart.

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:01.540
How should I say it, to be
honest and with good intentions.

00:02:02.220 --> 00:02:05.940
The fact that someone is my biggest
rival and that I want to beat him,

00:02:06.134 --> 00:02:09.461
doesn’t mean I wish him harm
in life or that I hate him.

00:02:09.709 --> 00:02:12.079
Or, I don’t know, anything else.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:14.938
Or that I would do something one way
or another so that he would lose

00:02:15.055 --> 00:02:16.782
to me on the court.

00:02:16.905 --> 00:02:22.665
On the court, we fight like knights,
one on one, and whoever wins wins.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:30.500
There’s a lot to it. Some things
aren’t meant to be shared.

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:37.254
Things I’ve felt through
those rivalries, and experienced.

00:02:41.278 --> 00:02:43.395
But that’s just how it is.

00:02:43.577 --> 00:02:47.897
Those two already had
a rivalry before I came along.

00:02:47.975 --> 00:02:51.815
Because Nadal had already
established himself years before me.

00:02:52.860 --> 00:02:57.960
The two of them came from Switzerland
and Spain. From two Western powers.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:05.835
As much as we want to see this world-
I don’t mean the tennis world-

00:03:05.942 --> 00:03:08.272
I mean the world in general...

00:03:08.366 --> 00:03:11.604
As democratic.
-As a place with equality.

00:03:13.072 --> 00:03:22.285
As peaceful-but unfortunately,
racism and boundaries still exist.

00:03:22.443 --> 00:03:24.332
And in that context...

00:03:25.264 --> 00:03:27.342
I’m not referring here
to racism I experienced.

00:03:27.479 --> 00:03:30.230
I’m talking about racism
as a phenomenon in society,

00:03:30.418 --> 00:03:33.379
in politics, and in everything
that’s happening globally.

00:03:34.752 --> 00:03:41.590
There are those affiliations and allegiances.
And I didn’t belong to that.

00:03:43.711 --> 00:03:48.613
So, neither by nationality
nor by many other things.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:53.420
By character, I was the young guy
who came in and said,

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:55.700
I’m going to be number one.

00:03:56.780 --> 00:03:59.660
They didn’t like that
from the very beginning.

00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:04.580
They didn’t like that I was there and
that now I was challenging those two.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:08.500
And second, like I said,
okay, now I’m...

00:04:09.340 --> 00:04:12.540
I respect and admire the two
of them, as I always have.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:16.060
I’ve never said a bad word about
either of them, and I never will.

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:19.460
Because I have self-respect.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:25.260
But I want to be better than them,
and I know I will be.

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:29.500
I have no problem saying that.
And I’ve always said it.

00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:34.420
But you have to be politically correct
in their kind of atmosphere.

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:40.235
And then, first the media starts,
then someone else, then the sponsors...

00:04:40.330 --> 00:04:42.808
Exactly. -And then the whole
machinery kicks in.

00:04:42.963 --> 00:04:45.995
Powerful sponsors, corporations
behind the tournaments.

00:04:46.153 --> 00:04:48.964
There are million things going on.
-Yes, this is...

00:04:49.164 --> 00:04:51.433
You’re fighting Goliath
and trying to be liked.

00:04:51.584 --> 00:04:55.953
And honestly, that’s why
I said it hurt me.

00:04:56.179 --> 00:05:01.880
Because I tried to connect with people
on a human level, not just with them.

00:05:02.319 --> 00:05:07.437
I simply noticed that it was a ruthless
competition and fight. A real war.

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:14.220
And I realized that, in a way,
I had to toughen up,

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:18.380
to shut myself off and go my own way.

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:23.700
But it's true I did try
to be liked by people a little.

00:05:23.980 --> 00:05:29.380
Then I realized there’s no need
to pretend. Because that wasn’t me.

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:35.340
Trying to be what they wanted.
They wanted me to play to their tune.

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:38.820
I admit it, that’s how it was.

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:44.220
Because I felt, like you said, like
an unwanted child. That’s how it felt.

00:05:46.897 --> 00:05:50.177
At that time, I kept thinking,
why is this happening?

00:05:50.431 --> 00:05:54.431
What did I do... -What was your crime?
...to provoke this?

00:05:54.704 --> 00:05:59.397
And it hurt me so much.
Okay, if they think...

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:02.820
Maybe they’ll accept me
if I behave differently.

00:06:02.997 --> 00:06:06.757
So I... you know what I mean?
Then it backfired on me. -Yes.

00:06:06.929 --> 00:06:12.129
Then I realized that a part
of the tennis and sports public

00:06:12.369 --> 00:06:15.889
would never accept or love me
because of my attitudes,

00:06:16.073 --> 00:06:18.219
behavior, and whatever else.

00:06:18.450 --> 00:06:21.477
But I am who I am, and I sleep
peacefully. -That’s right.

00:06:21.903 --> 00:06:25.333
Okay, later on, that relationship
between you changed.

00:06:27.179 --> 00:06:28.859
I want to tell you...

00:06:29.341 --> 00:06:33.419
My attitude toward them in
that sense never changed. -No.

00:06:33.817 --> 00:06:37.857
The situation changed because
their attitude toward me changed.

00:06:38.177 --> 00:06:42.857
I always tried to be,
how should I put it...

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:47.060
I looked up to them.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:50.696
And I still look at them as people
who paved the way for me.

00:06:50.821 --> 00:06:53.075
Especially Federer, who is
six years older than me. -Yes.

00:06:53.193 --> 00:06:58.713
The moment I felt that coldness
and distance from him,

00:06:58.828 --> 00:07:00.729
I said, alright, no problem.

00:07:00.888 --> 00:07:05.221
And the moment they approached me,
I opened my arms and said, okay.

00:07:05.390 --> 00:07:12.110
Now they’ve both retired, and with Nadal,
I always kind of understood him better.

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:15.420
We’re about the same age,
so maybe that’s why.

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:21.780
But the media later
also had to eat their words.

00:07:22.060 --> 00:07:25.660
Because at the end of the day,
tennis is a measurable sport.

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:30.140
You can’t ignore something-
as the Italians say, carta canta.

00:07:30.439 --> 00:07:32.599
That’s right.
-You can’t deny it.

00:07:32.826 --> 00:07:38.835
Now, when you look, they’re no longer
on the court. They’re not competing.

00:07:39.278 --> 00:07:44.585
From this perspective, how did you
view the three of you as players?

00:07:45.070 --> 00:07:50.110
Where did you think you dominated?
What were you better at than them?

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:53.340
I don’t mean the surface
you played on.

00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:59.591
And which territory didn’t you want to enter
because they were better at it than you?

00:08:00.827 --> 00:08:08.077
For example, Nadal once said:
"With Roger, it was...

00:08:08.475 --> 00:08:11.210
He always says Novak is
the best for him. Why?

00:08:11.549 --> 00:08:18.429
With Roger, the tactic was clear.
Play to the backhand and wait for the chance.

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:22.660
But with Novak, I can’t play to
the backhand or the forehand.

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:26.590
I can’t play high balls.
I can’t even go for angles.

00:08:26.712 --> 00:08:31.681
Because if it’s not a perfect shot,
it opens up a chance for him to score.

00:08:31.845 --> 00:08:38.405
So I just have to play down the middle,
but at an insanely high level,

00:08:38.558 --> 00:08:40.318
and wait for my chance."

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:44.580
Yes. -So where did you see yourself
in comparison to them?

00:08:48.220 --> 00:08:54.140
I’m glad that Nadal saw and felt
it that way, because my goal was

00:08:54.420 --> 00:08:59.020
and the people around me too
to create exactly that feeling in him,

00:08:59.220 --> 00:09:01.780
and in every player I play against.

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:07.020
In the sense that I have enough
options in my game.

00:09:07.300 --> 00:09:12.180
And that my game
is as complete as possible.

00:09:15.974 --> 00:09:21.138
Meaning, that my game isn’t based
on the type of surface I'm playing on.

00:09:21.377 --> 00:09:24.617
But that it’s all-round,
as the English say.

00:09:24.935 --> 00:09:32.216
That my game can be applied to all
types of surfaces and in all conditions.

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:36.505
That took years to build.

00:09:37.121 --> 00:09:43.361
Even when I won my first Grand Slam,
I still wasn’t playing that way.

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:46.916
It wasn’t until 2011
that I started playing like that.

00:09:47.036 --> 00:09:49.440
That was the first time I had
one of the best seasons.

00:09:49.554 --> 00:09:53.744
Only then did I reach
that level of play.

00:09:54.255 --> 00:09:57.975
That’s when I truly felt
that no one could beat me.

00:09:59.350 --> 00:10:04.793
Whatever happens, I always have a solution
no matter who I’m playing or how.

00:10:05.049 --> 00:10:09.769
What I always tried to develop...

00:10:10.538 --> 00:10:14.458
Again, I’ll go back to Jelena Genčić
and also Nikola Pilić.

00:10:14.792 --> 00:10:18.952
I think they helped me a lot,
especially in developing

00:10:19.340 --> 00:10:22.100
my ability to adapt.

00:10:23.620 --> 00:10:28.300
To have my game, my base,
but also to be able to adjust tactically

00:10:28.540 --> 00:10:31.860
depending on who is
on the other side of the net.

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:35.180
And how I need to
approach that match.

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:39.940
That’s one of the traits I’m very
proud of, and it’s helped me a lot.

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:44.860
Even in preserving energy,
no matter how exhausted I was, etc.

00:10:45.358 --> 00:10:47.580
When we compare me,
Federer, and Nadal...

00:10:47.718 --> 00:10:52.210
Federer is the most talented one,
the most beautiful to watch when playing,

00:10:52.358 --> 00:10:55.238
he used his energy most efficiently.

00:10:55.453 --> 00:11:00.666
He moved lightly, so elegantly,
and so efficiently.

00:11:02.807 --> 00:11:09.570
While Nadal is the opposite extreme.
He dominated physically.

00:11:10.247 --> 00:11:12.938
I was somewhere in between,
but I leaned more toward

00:11:12.998 --> 00:11:14.805
Nadal’s style of play.

00:11:14.966 --> 00:11:18.961
So, more sliding, more running,
baseline-focused play, and so on.

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:26.477
Each of us had our own characteristics,
and over time, as our rivalries

00:11:26.586 --> 00:11:29.180
developed, they evolved
and strengthened.

00:11:29.504 --> 00:11:34.016
We always say that, all three of us,
and I know they’ve said it too.

00:11:34.318 --> 00:11:39.230
Through those rivalries, we each
contributed to one another’s growth

00:11:39.371 --> 00:11:43.278
as tennis players, and as people.

00:11:43.609 --> 00:11:50.729
Absolutely. -I say it without hesitation
my rivalry with those two had the biggest

00:11:50.936 --> 00:11:53.376
influence on my development.

00:11:53.569 --> 00:11:59.348
Especially in the second part
of my career, from 2011 onward.

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:06.740
I don’t even know which moments
I’d single out-for example, with Nadal-

00:12:06.862 --> 00:12:09.142
when you walk out onto center
court at Roland Garros,

00:12:09.241 --> 00:12:14.590
you don’t feel indifferent.
Everyone says that to you.

00:12:16.322 --> 00:12:21.063
Perception plays a huge role-
I mean visual perception.

00:12:21.425 --> 00:12:28.313
For example, if you’re playing
a tournament in Geneva, also on clay...

00:12:28.836 --> 00:12:36.915
There, the side fences and
the back wall are fairly close.

00:12:37.485 --> 00:12:41.649
Within regulation dimensions,
but minimal.

00:12:42.100 --> 00:12:45.562
Whereas at Roland Garros, it feels like
you’re walking onto a football field.

00:12:45.729 --> 00:12:47.661
There’s an extra 15 meters
behind the baseline,

00:12:47.869 --> 00:12:49.869
and just as much to the left and right.

00:12:50.423 --> 00:12:55.140
He played deep behind the baseline
and spun that topspin,

00:12:55.439 --> 00:13:00.429
where the ball kicks up off the clay
and sends you back every time.

00:13:00.912 --> 00:13:05.432
At that time, I felt like I just couldn’t
"break through", no matter what.

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:07.680
He would reach every ball.

00:13:07.912 --> 00:13:13.152
And with his visual perception of the
court, that is so deep on the sides

00:13:13.275 --> 00:13:17.819
and behind him, it made it
even harder for you to hit a winner

00:13:17.913 --> 00:13:22.094
or do something because you felt
it was three times more difficult.

00:13:22.187 --> 00:13:24.914
That's exactly how it was for me
in football. -Isn't it?

00:13:25.015 --> 00:13:30.068
We went from West Ham's stadium,
that narrow English-style ground...

00:13:30.113 --> 00:13:31.802
Yes, yes, the narrow one...

00:13:31.881 --> 00:13:36.209
...to the Olympic Stadium in London,
which West Ham rented for 100 years.

00:13:36.386 --> 00:13:39.466
And you're in the same position
as on that old pitch,

00:13:39.534 --> 00:13:44.054
the field is the same size,
but you feel like there's no way

00:13:44.112 --> 00:13:47.482
you can get to the penalty box in time,
even though it's actually the same.

00:13:47.636 --> 00:13:51.170
Yes, it's the same. -Sorry to interrupt.
-No, absolutely. -It's the same!

00:13:51.331 --> 00:14:00.229
Yes. That's a moment I would highlight
as something really significant.

00:14:00.458 --> 00:14:03.205
It was a huge challenge for me.

00:14:03.410 --> 00:14:09.666
I think I'm the only player who managed
to beat him 3 or 4 times on that court.

00:14:10.896 --> 00:14:13.963
Or take Federer at Wimbledon,
for example.

00:14:14.152 --> 00:14:17.072
I had more success against Federer
on the Wimbledon center court,

00:14:17.265 --> 00:14:20.838
I think I lost to him once,
but I beat him four or five times.

00:14:20.968 --> 00:14:26.808
Every time I played him on the center
court at Wimbledon, it was just...

00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:32.400
You know when you have some matches,
or in your sport some games,

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:37.080
where you feel everything is vibrating.

00:14:37.304 --> 00:14:41.551
Even before you step on the court,
in the locker room,

00:14:42.380 --> 00:14:47.420
the whole day feels like
something special is happening,

00:14:47.700 --> 00:14:52.060
like an out-of-body experience, from the
people, to the media, to everything...

00:14:52.300 --> 00:14:57.020
Everything tingles, you know, because
you feel the uniqueness of the moment.

00:14:57.220 --> 00:15:01.620
Especially since Federer and I played
3 Wimbledon finals against each other.

00:15:02.249 --> 00:15:04.219
It's like, you know,
playing Federer at Wimbledon,

00:15:04.343 --> 00:15:06.343
the most successful player ever,
on grass...

00:15:06.466 --> 00:15:09.571
Wimbledon was always Federer's court.
-Yes, yes.

00:15:09.663 --> 00:15:11.946
While Roland Garros was Nadal's court.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:19.660
Because of Wimbledon being Federer's
and Roland Garros being Nadal's court,

00:15:19.784 --> 00:15:23.985
I knew I wouldn't have the majority
of the crowd on my side in any match.

00:15:24.179 --> 00:15:28.420
It was like that from start to finish,
until the very last point.

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:36.060
And that really got to me at first,
I couldn't overcome it because

00:15:36.237 --> 00:15:39.517
I was fighting both against them
and against myself.

00:15:39.623 --> 00:15:43.944
People say: "Novak needs to be provoked
to bring out the best in himself."

00:15:44.100 --> 00:15:49.967
In some situations, at some moments
maybe that was true, and it did happen,

00:15:50.180 --> 00:15:53.660
but it's not what I want.
Who wants to step out...

00:15:53.860 --> 00:15:57.740
For example, imagine you step out
at the Bernabéu stadium

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:00.908
and 80,000 people boo you, and you have
to play every match in those conditions.

00:16:01.021 --> 00:16:03.021
You understand me?
It's not that easy.

00:16:03.245 --> 00:16:05.925
You have to get used to it,
and how you adapt to that

00:16:06.109 --> 00:16:09.573
determines the outcome of everything.
-Yes, that's tough.

00:16:09.790 --> 00:16:16.750
Tell me, now that they're not here,
has a part of you gone too?

00:16:17.037 --> 00:16:21.995
Do you see parts of them in
Sinner or Alcaraz? It's not the same...

00:16:22.222 --> 00:16:26.742
No, it's not the same. -It can't be...
-It's not the same.

00:16:27.140 --> 00:16:32.302
Sinner and Alcaraz are truly
exceptional, outstanding players.

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:35.860
I'm sure we'll be seeing them
for many years to come

00:16:36.100 --> 00:16:45.260
as the leaders of the sport, tennis. For
me, Federer and Nadal are irreplaceable,

00:16:45.580 --> 00:16:48.940
and a large part of me left with them.

00:16:49.300 --> 00:16:54.300
And as Federer left,
and as Nadal gradually stepped away,

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:58.340
not officially retired yet,
but even when he was still around,

00:16:58.580 --> 00:17:02.260
I felt different than I do today,
after he's completely gone.

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:06.260
I really am different. I thought it
wouldn't be like that, but it is...

00:17:06.500 --> 00:17:10.420
You know what I'm curious about?
Everything, of course...

00:17:11.340 --> 00:17:14.943
As the English say,
'Heavy lies the crown'.

00:17:15.529 --> 00:17:23.462
I told a few friends you were coming,
and they all told me to ask you this...

00:17:24.231 --> 00:17:30.649
We understand the first Grand Slam,
the second, third, and fourth,

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:37.260
because you're the best player, because
you're talented. But how 24? How?

00:17:39.700 --> 00:17:48.180
How is it possible to stay focused
in this sport to win it 24 times?

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:53.260
I'm an athlete, I know how
success can intoxicate you,

00:17:53.460 --> 00:17:56.340
and how you want to repeat it
over and over again.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:18:01.540
Take Luka Modrić's jersey,
and his words,

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:08.420
or Kukoč's about Jordan, about
building that dynasty, as they say.

00:18:10.140 --> 00:18:12.580
It's easier somehow...

00:18:12.940 --> 00:18:16.140
You can win the World Cup
as a footballer even if you played

00:18:16.340 --> 00:18:18.300
an average tournament.

00:18:18.540 --> 00:18:22.300
You can win the Champions League after
30% of your matches were poor,

00:18:22.468 --> 00:18:26.668
or even an entire weak season,
but a teammate pulls you through,

00:18:26.829 --> 00:18:31.930
the team pulls you through, you push
each other. But in tennis, you're alone,

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:35.539
and you constantly have to be
focused at that level.

00:18:35.705 --> 00:18:38.505
How is that possible?
Explain that to us.

00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:51.660
I think that question, especially in
today's world and the last 10-20 years,

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:56.500
when professional sports
like the global ones you mentioned

00:18:56.740 --> 00:19:06.340
really demand that you be completely
professional off the court,

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:11.980
not just on the court. On the court,
it's what they call 'a must',

00:19:12.220 --> 00:19:15.100
something you have to do,
something logical.

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:18.740
But what matters is
what you do off the court.

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:23.356
That's always been something
that buzzes in my ears.

00:19:23.520 --> 00:19:29.610
From a young age, I was lucky, you
talked about luck, and I agree with you

00:19:29.884 --> 00:19:36.719
that you need to be fortunate
first and foremost, to be surrounded by

00:19:37.509 --> 00:19:44.368
the right people who will guide you,
show you, point things out,

00:19:44.868 --> 00:19:53.180
and who will let you fall and learn,
who will enrich your life

00:19:53.567 --> 00:19:55.607
but not make it easy.

00:19:55.940 --> 00:20:01.940
Enrich in the sense of making you
stronger, more capable,

00:20:02.860 --> 00:20:06.700
and more complete as a person
and as an athlete.

00:20:07.260 --> 00:20:15.700
So, I think maybe the secret of success,
not just mine but of top-level athletes,

00:20:15.902 --> 00:20:22.673
especially in individual sports is that
you find a formula that works for you.

00:20:22.954 --> 00:20:30.834
In my case, because of the circumstances
of my upbringing and where I come from,

00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:40.620
I was simply forced to adapt
my entire life to tennis.

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:44.900
When I say 'entire life'
I really mean the whole thing. So...

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:50.620
We talked about the teenage years you
mentioned, all those outings and so on,

00:20:51.940 --> 00:20:56.180
I didn't have that,
not to mention alcohol...

00:20:56.420 --> 00:21:07.611
Sure, I did drink and had a few nights
when I relaxed a bit, and that's normal.

00:21:08.309 --> 00:21:11.652
You need to have a way to 'vent'.
-Of course.

00:21:13.700 --> 00:21:18.300
But 95% of the time, what really matters
is how you spend your time.

00:21:18.660 --> 00:21:22.820
How do you spend your time
in quarantine?

00:21:23.020 --> 00:21:27.220
How do you spend it
during training periods?

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:38.135
Are you doing things that fill your
life, your mind, and your emotions

00:21:39.180 --> 00:21:44.540
with good energy or not? I think
every athlete should ask themselves:

00:21:44.740 --> 00:21:49.100
what do you do with your time?
Not just what you eat or drink,

00:21:49.380 --> 00:21:55.740
but who you spend your time with,
those people around you who can be

00:21:56.020 --> 00:22:05.300
family or friends... Family is family,
but who are the people you choose to

00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:10.900
surround yourself with? What kind of
conversations do you have with them?

00:22:11.100 --> 00:22:15.300
Become aware of that.
You know, for a long time,

00:22:16.060 --> 00:22:20.500
I didn't understand the strength,
the power, and importance of realizing

00:22:20.740 --> 00:22:29.635
that the topics I devote my vitality
and life energy to actually affect

00:22:29.979 --> 00:22:34.956
my performance on the court tomorrow,
they absolutely do! All the news I read,

00:22:35.180 --> 00:22:40.420
the topics I engage with, the people I
talk about, whether I mention politics

00:22:40.620 --> 00:22:44.540
or something else, or whether I choose
to talk about something more positive...

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:50.020
Do you understand me? We're all human,
and it's difficult in these times...

00:22:50.260 --> 00:22:55.740
I say many things are easier for
athletes in the last 15 years or so,

00:22:56.500 --> 00:23:02.060
but mentally and emotionally, they're
much harder than they were for us.

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:08.180
I'm younger than you, but I was still
in that era without mobile phones...

00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:14.855
Now social media is here,
and I catch myself losing hours on it,

00:23:15.058 --> 00:23:19.473
and then I suddenly
snap back to reality and say,

00:23:19.653 --> 00:23:22.413
'Man, where did my time go?
What did I do?'

00:23:22.551 --> 00:23:26.199
100%, but where does your focus come
from to keep it going for so long?

00:23:26.319 --> 00:23:28.777
Well, you practice it.
Slaven, you practice it, man.

00:23:28.887 --> 00:23:31.918
It's like practicing a shot or a stroke.

00:23:32.024 --> 00:23:37.584
Yes, but there's that paradox,
you obviously had dreams...

00:23:37.832 --> 00:23:42.472
You know, nowadays everything is
explained with terms like

00:23:42.696 --> 00:23:48.536
'comfort zone.' Don't stay in your
comfort zone because that's bad. -Yes.

00:23:48.728 --> 00:23:51.840
And one of the reasons you do something,
not the only one, of course,

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:55.100
but alongside your dreams,
is to secure a comfortable life

00:23:55.286 --> 00:23:59.686
for yourself and your loved ones.
And once you get that opportunity,

00:23:59.803 --> 00:24:02.290
you run away from your comfort zone.

00:24:02.471 --> 00:24:04.610
Under no circumstances
should you stay there

00:24:04.775 --> 00:24:09.055
because that's a guarantee of failure.
-Yes. -How do you resist all of that...?

00:24:09.188 --> 00:24:16.562
You know, I've talked generally about
being aware of the moment and your life.

00:24:16.935 --> 00:24:21.578
In the sense of how consciously
you make decisions,

00:24:21.828 --> 00:24:26.180
or how much someone else influences
your decisions, whoever it is.

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:33.260
Whether your friends call you out for
coffee, or maybe you can use that time

00:24:33.420 --> 00:24:36.860
for something that's good for you,
even if it's just sleeping,

00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:42.828
which is very useful. You don't have to
constantly sit and study or whatever,

00:24:43.102 --> 00:24:46.955
but it's important to organize
your time and ask yourself:

00:24:47.125 --> 00:24:51.188
If I can't set aside time
to do something for myself,

00:24:51.420 --> 00:24:56.540
but I have to go somewhere else,
am I living the life I want to live,

00:24:56.690 --> 00:25:00.898
in a way that makes sense
for my profession and career?

00:25:01.017 --> 00:25:06.540
Or am I living just to belong to that
group, afraid of being rejected,

00:25:06.687 --> 00:25:11.007
afraid they won't be my friends
tomorrow? That's one thing...

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:16.260
Now, when we talk about this here,
it might seem like a light topic

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:19.660
and maybe not that important,
but it is very important. -It is.

00:25:19.860 --> 00:25:24.100
We're social beings. In sports,
especially individual sports,

00:25:24.300 --> 00:25:30.300
we're often lonely. I sometimes say I
envy footballers and basketball players

00:25:30.580 --> 00:25:36.140
for their amazing communities and
friendships. Thank God, I have that too,

00:25:36.340 --> 00:25:40.300
not that I don't, but that's
the beauty of team sports.

00:25:40.500 --> 00:25:44.900
But it can also drag you down if they
aren't willing to live in a way

00:25:45.100 --> 00:25:53.653
you can and feel you should, but you
don't because, well, most don't.

00:25:54.481 --> 00:25:57.200
And if most are like that,
then I'll be like that too.

00:25:57.485 --> 00:26:02.285
Now it’s already a bit of psychology
and philosophy. This second thing

00:26:02.464 --> 00:26:05.704
you asked me about, about how
to find new motivation if you’ve

00:26:05.872 --> 00:26:08.032
already achieved something,
and how to keep going afterward.

00:26:08.224 --> 00:26:11.022
Above all, for me, it’s love
and passion for the sport.

00:26:12.420 --> 00:26:16.540
I love tennis because I love tennis.
I love holding the racket and playing.

00:26:16.820 --> 00:26:21.940
That boy is still in me who
fell in love with tennis. I still feel it.

00:26:22.340 --> 00:26:26.798
That connection. And secondly,
if I didn’t have the passion

00:26:26.916 --> 00:26:29.594
and desire to compete, I wouldn’t
be playing professionally,

00:26:29.748 --> 00:26:31.428
I’d just be doing it casually.

00:26:31.558 --> 00:26:35.814
But I still feel that passion, it still
drives me crazy when someone beats me,

00:26:36.263 --> 00:26:39.863
and I still want to outsmart someone
on the court and do whatever I can

00:26:39.977 --> 00:26:42.509
with the racket in my hands
to win that match.

00:26:42.818 --> 00:26:49.001
That still tells me the fire
in me is still there.

00:26:49.391 --> 00:26:51.511
That flame is burning.

00:26:52.104 --> 00:26:58.624
Of course, if you have a purpose,
which I think must come from emotion,

00:26:59.083 --> 00:27:05.123
it must come from some depth.
Then after that, you ask yourself

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:11.660
if you have some clear visions,
meaning goals. Because goals matter.

00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:16.260
Dreams matter. -That’s right.
-They drive you on a general level,

00:27:16.460 --> 00:27:22.180
but short-term goals matter too.
They’re also important.

00:27:22.389 --> 00:27:26.749
When we’re talking about weeks,
months, or years, you know-this season.

00:27:26.888 --> 00:27:33.568
You have some clarity. You wake up
and say, OK, my goal is to get there.

00:27:33.810 --> 00:27:38.090
Right now I’m here, starting point.
What can I do to get there

00:27:38.361 --> 00:27:43.081
in the best possible way
within the time I want?

00:27:43.460 --> 00:27:47.420
To be at my peak, to play at
the Grand Slams then and there,

00:27:47.620 --> 00:27:51.660
to give myself the best chance
to become what I want to be.

00:27:51.829 --> 00:27:56.629
Those are the things... it’s a process,
a mental one I feel I go through,

00:27:56.869 --> 00:28:03.589
and it helps me be at peace
with some of my decisions.

00:28:03.719 --> 00:28:06.719
And the part from the start
of the conversation,

00:28:06.855 --> 00:28:10.377
maybe that’s a bit broader
and for another time.

00:28:11.940 --> 00:28:15.740
You said that one time,
back in 2016. -Yes.

00:28:17.380 --> 00:28:22.340
That from 2014 to 2016
you maybe played your best tennis.

00:28:22.580 --> 00:28:27.620
You won six Grand Slams.
That’s epic, a rhapsody.

00:28:28.420 --> 00:28:31.700
In 2016, you won Roland Garros
for the first time.

00:28:32.660 --> 00:28:39.740
Back then you said you lost that
energy and motivation for a moment,

00:28:40.020 --> 00:28:44.700
and you asked yourself: What now? -Yes.
-What happened, and how did you get it back?

00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:51.839
Wimbledon, after winning Roland Garros.
Wimbledon came soon after,

00:28:52.353 --> 00:28:58.612
a few weeks later. That’s both
the blessing and the curse of tennis.

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:03.820
You always have another big chance
very quickly, but precisely because

00:29:04.060 --> 00:29:06.420
something big is coming right away,
it’s also a curse-

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:11.460
because you can’t really celebrate
what you just achieved.

00:29:11.740 --> 00:29:16.780
I won a Grand Slam, I held all four.
People even told me:

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:19.820
"If you want to skip Wimbledon
and not play for the rest of the season,

00:29:20.020 --> 00:29:24.380
that’s fine. You’ve already done
what you set out to do." But...

00:29:25.780 --> 00:29:28.900
How can you not play Wimbledon?
-How do you skip Wimbledon?

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:35.060
That’s just... you always wonder
will there be another chance at Wimbledon?

00:29:35.260 --> 00:29:40.860
These are the things constantly
circling in an athlete’s head.

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:48.580
I played the third round, Court 1.
Three rain delays.

00:29:49.500 --> 00:29:54.700
I had a tricky opponent,
strong, fast serve, American.

00:29:55.100 --> 00:30:01.860
Always tough on grass, and so on.
He won the first set, then two sets.

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:10.340
First delay was mid-second set.
My team came in while we waited.

00:30:10.900 --> 00:30:14.940
In that little room nearby.
I talked to them, frustrated

00:30:15.030 --> 00:30:19.350
with how I was playing, some stretching,
planning, we keep going.

00:30:19.457 --> 00:30:21.657
I came back, won the third set.

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:26.620
I had momentum, started feeling
and playing better.

00:30:26.900 --> 00:30:29.980
It was close in the fourth set,
on the edge of breaking through-

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:34.940
but I didn’t manage to.
And rain again.

00:30:38.340 --> 00:30:44.220
Team came in, I said: "Guys,
please, let me be alone a little."

00:30:44.780 --> 00:30:51.020
"Do you need anything?" "Nothing."
I need peace, I need to stare at the wall.

00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:57.074
There was a TV there,
but I didn’t want anything.

00:30:57.801 --> 00:31:03.160
At that moment, for the first time
in my life, I left my bags.

00:31:03.525 --> 00:31:11.065
There wasn’t even a chair, just
a massage table. I didn’t lift the backrest,

00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:15.860
just lay down like this.
Stared at the ceiling, at the wall.

00:31:16.072 --> 00:31:19.619
For about 20 minutes,
half an hour. I didn’t move.

00:31:19.815 --> 00:31:24.627
Muscles cool off, usually you stretch.
I didn’t want anything.

00:31:25.464 --> 00:31:32.064
At that moment, I experienced
a kind of emptiness.

00:31:33.660 --> 00:31:36.340
Then I lost the match
when I went back.

00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:43.423
I simply felt like... now what?
I don’t know how to define it.

00:31:44.885 --> 00:31:52.223
But again, like I explained before,
the moment of winning my first Slam,

00:31:52.340 --> 00:31:55.500
then feeling for the first time
what it means to defend a title-

00:31:55.700 --> 00:32:00.420
this was something new I unlocked,
something I never had before.

00:32:00.559 --> 00:32:02.919
A new emotion, new feelings.

00:32:03.140 --> 00:32:09.130
Now I wrote history, I’d achieved
pretty much everything there is to achieve-

00:32:09.325 --> 00:32:15.060
and now what?
Then I basically had to go through

00:32:15.300 --> 00:32:19.740
some internal transition.
To work on all of that

00:32:19.940 --> 00:32:22.860
in order to come back again.

00:32:23.073 --> 00:32:32.873
Maybe the whole process lasted
from late 2016 to mid-2018.

00:32:34.580 --> 00:32:38.060
I played, got injured,
had that elbow injury

00:32:38.300 --> 00:32:42.380
which made me rest for six months.
I had surgery, and so on.

00:32:42.580 --> 00:32:45.973
Then I had trouble, my serve
changed because of the injury,

00:32:46.099 --> 00:32:48.270
I dropped out of the top 20.

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:56.700
I wanted to quit tennis in 2018.
In March, I lost first round in Miami.

00:32:56.980 --> 00:33:00.660
I said: I can’t, I need
to go somewhere.

00:33:01.300 --> 00:33:04.980
Then I went with the family
to the Dominican Republic,

00:33:05.180 --> 00:33:07.300
to a friend’s place.
There was a tennis court there.

00:33:07.500 --> 00:33:10.620
They started playing.
After I don’t know how many days off,

00:33:10.860 --> 00:33:14.340
I didn’t even want to come near,
didn’t want anything to do with tennis.

00:33:16.700 --> 00:33:21.180
My wife was playing. I watched,
she was playing with our son.

00:33:21.660 --> 00:33:30.490
I asked: "Can I?" She said: "No. Stefan
and I are playing now." -Wait your turn.

00:33:32.260 --> 00:33:36.900
They finished, and then I stayed.
My son stayed a bit and played with me.

00:33:37.060 --> 00:33:41.940
I told them to go, I’d stay alone.
I took the basket and barefoot, in trunks,

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:48.220
I started serving. One, two,
five serves-stayed two hours alone.

00:33:48.580 --> 00:33:54.500
It slowly came back.
Then from 20-something in the world

00:33:54.740 --> 00:34:00.460
back to number one by year’s end.
That was probably my biggest comeback ever.

00:34:01.300 --> 00:34:07.071
Every phase has its why.
You just have to somehow-

00:34:07.460 --> 00:34:12.860
that’s my life lesson-
give a chance to both life and God

00:34:13.060 --> 00:34:17.500
to sort things out for you.
Sometimes it’s better to let go,

00:34:17.725 --> 00:34:20.525
and then receive. -Yeah. Bravo.

00:34:22.060 --> 00:34:27.380
You once said-earlier you said-
that curse of being first.

00:34:27.660 --> 00:34:32.260
That feeling when you win a Grand Slam
for the first time, and then next time

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:37.900
you’re the target,
so to speak, that everyone wants.

00:34:40.900 --> 00:34:44.700
You say tennis is a mental sport.

00:34:45.220 --> 00:34:50.220
You say that in every single match
you go through

00:34:51.140 --> 00:34:56.260
ups and downs, turbulence, frustration-
both mental and physical. -Yes.

00:34:56.500 --> 00:35:00.620
You say those create fears
and doubts. In every match.

00:35:00.820 --> 00:35:07.020
You simply have to get away from there,
think of something nice and escape.

00:35:07.260 --> 00:35:14.048
You also say that the optimal state
in which every tennis player should be

00:35:14.221 --> 00:35:17.661
is now. -Yes. -Not thinking about what
has happened or what will happen.

00:35:17.876 --> 00:35:26.058
Well, life is like that too. Lennon said
that people spend their lives analyzing

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:31.715
the past and planning the future.
That's the same thing you just said.

00:35:31.936 --> 00:35:41.178
But, how... OK, now you have the experience
and all. How did you reach that level

00:35:41.502 --> 00:35:44.782
where you’re able to reset,
during a match,

00:35:45.140 --> 00:35:48.100
where your pulse is 200,
adrenaline, everything?

00:35:48.300 --> 00:35:54.460
To reset and ignore something
that happened 30 seconds ago.

00:35:54.820 --> 00:36:02.220
Or a minute. -I always go back to one
interesting story of my friend.

00:36:06.474 --> 00:36:12.820
He goes to a Buddhist Zen temple.
He is in France and his

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:21.140
spiritual teacher is in the French
mountains. He goes to visit him.

00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:30.738
From time to time he spends days there.
He goes to isolate himself a bit,

00:36:30.928 --> 00:36:35.848
to clear his mind and so on.
The first few times he went there,

00:36:37.580 --> 00:36:42.460
he noticed how calm
that spiritual teacher is,

00:36:43.580 --> 00:36:48.460
how nothing disturbs him,
how he doesn’t react to anything.

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:53.660
And not just there, but when they go
to the city, when they’re in crowds,

00:36:53.900 --> 00:36:58.380
when he experiences some everyday things,
because they are also friends.

00:36:58.700 --> 00:37:02.940
Then he asked him once
if he would tell him what it is

00:37:03.220 --> 00:37:08.940
that you do and how is it possible
that you don’t react to anything, man.

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:14.235
That nothing really disturbs you.
People bump into your window in traffic,

00:37:14.400 --> 00:37:19.140
they honk at you, want to break your glass,
and you’re like, nothing, it’s all good.

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:23.620
Calm, peaceful, serene.
How is it possible that you don’t have

00:37:23.820 --> 00:37:27.980
those negative thoughts? He told him,
my friend, you’re wrong.

00:37:28.380 --> 00:37:33.260
I do have those negative thoughts,
probably more than you do.

00:37:33.580 --> 00:37:38.140
But the difference between you and me
is that I stay in them

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:47.380
less than a second. Then I return back.
That training I did - actually he did it,

00:37:48.500 --> 00:37:55.580
gives me the benefits of being able
and allows me, gives me the tools,

00:37:55.900 --> 00:38:01.620
to return instantly
to that kind of optimal state.

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:08.980
Calm state. And you stay in it.
Some people stay in it their whole life.

00:38:09.500 --> 00:38:14.220
In some emotion of sadness,
anger, rage, whatever.

00:38:14.820 --> 00:38:19.700
The reason I just told this
is because I like to go back to it

00:38:21.300 --> 00:38:27.220
and to think about how life
is actually just a moment.

00:38:28.620 --> 00:38:35.060
Life is here and now. The past
is something that already happened,

00:38:35.260 --> 00:38:40.020
the future is yet to happen.
And Lennon was right.

00:38:40.300 --> 00:38:46.100
People, all of us, including me,
constantly walk between the past

00:38:46.300 --> 00:38:50.900
and the future. On the court,
that is even more noticeable.

00:38:51.300 --> 00:38:57.180
I think about what maybe I could’ve
done in that previous point,

00:38:57.380 --> 00:39:07.340
game, set. Or anxiety and fear arise from
the unpredictability of the next moment.

00:39:08.380 --> 00:39:12.192
Whether it will go this way or that,
or the wind will blow this or that way.

00:39:12.360 --> 00:39:14.640
Or, I don’t even know
what might happen.

00:39:17.660 --> 00:39:23.860
﻿I really tried, through my own life
and career experience,

00:39:24.420 --> 00:39:27.820
to be as present as much
as I can here and now.

00:39:30.500 --> 00:39:35.260
That’s a mindset I inherited
from Jelena and Niki,

00:39:35.460 --> 00:39:38.220
and of course my parents
from the very beginning,

00:39:38.420 --> 00:39:42.980
and from all the people I met,
worked with, and learned from.

00:39:43.180 --> 00:39:48.589
All of that, in some way,
enabled and helped me

00:39:50.060 --> 00:39:54.380
to shape myself,
my character and personality.

00:39:54.700 --> 00:39:59.780
There are things I do,
conscious breathing, prayer,

00:40:00.016 --> 00:40:02.256
visualizing the space...

00:40:02.535 --> 00:40:06.135
Those are various techniques,
as I call them,

00:40:07.055 --> 00:40:13.295
which don’t always help.

00:40:15.094 --> 00:40:18.512
Life is more than that.
You can't just "live",

00:40:18.993 --> 00:40:22.646
because everything is relative,
and upside down.

00:40:22.768 --> 00:40:25.328
And then you get on the court
and you pray:

00:40:25.512 --> 00:40:28.568
"Lord, help me, help me, help me."
That’s how it is.

00:40:28.898 --> 00:40:32.318
So it’s very important to take
everything into account,

00:40:32.454 --> 00:40:35.239
because everything matters.
What matters the most?

00:40:35.444 --> 00:40:38.888
I don’t know - everything matters.
When you think about it...

00:40:39.111 --> 00:40:41.231
It's important how you live,
how you sleep,

00:40:41.331 --> 00:40:43.211
everything is absolutely important.

00:40:43.365 --> 00:40:46.537
Because it all reflects on how you feel,
who you are as a person,

00:40:46.653 --> 00:40:50.653
and then that either helps or
hinders you on your court. -True.

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:54.740
So, in that context,
I think it's something that,

00:40:55.180 --> 00:41:02.820
if you're aware of it, and it helped me,
and I always say this,

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:08.740
50% of victory is achieved
before you step on the court.

00:41:09.340 --> 00:41:11.540
At least 50%, at least.

00:41:11.820 --> 00:41:16.660
Because if you define that prep,
mental, physical, emotional,

00:41:16.900 --> 00:41:20.100
tactical, technical,
whatever angle you take,

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:24.100
it reflects afterward
on your perception of Wembley

00:41:24.340 --> 00:41:26.700
or what you said about West Ham.

00:41:26.940 --> 00:41:29.740
Will that consume you,
or will you say:

00:41:29.980 --> 00:41:33.660
"Wait, this is really how it is,
but I’m going to adapt now.

00:41:33.900 --> 00:41:37.260
Yes, it's a new situation,
something I haven’t prepared for,

00:41:37.398 --> 00:41:41.203
but I’ll adapt quickly, whatever it is."

00:41:41.269 --> 00:41:43.606
Like the art of war.

00:41:44.090 --> 00:41:48.614
In that case, the war is won
before it even begins.

00:41:49.935 --> 00:41:55.121
The proof is what you said,
those are your words.

00:41:55.566 --> 00:41:58.966
Tennis is a mental sport,
everyone is ready,

00:41:59.088 --> 00:42:01.675
everyone hits
forehand and backhand.

00:42:01.971 --> 00:42:06.761
There are many players
who play phenomenally in training...

00:42:07.005 --> 00:42:09.106
Now explain this stat to me...

00:42:09.243 --> 00:42:13.563
I can’t process it,
so explain it to me, please.

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:20.300
I read it and it’s true, it’s a stat.
The percentage of points won,

00:42:20.500 --> 00:42:24.380
albeit across a career,
at the beginning there were no wins,

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:31.060
yours, Nadal's, and Federer's
were at 54% and 55%. -Yes.

00:42:31.420 --> 00:42:36.700
I’d have guessed 70%.
How is that possible?

00:42:37.060 --> 00:42:39.220
It’s interesting.

00:42:43.540 --> 00:42:48.020
In the end, when you draw
the line and look at it,

00:42:48.340 --> 00:42:56.140
which that stat confirms,
what distinguishes elite

00:42:56.340 --> 00:43:04.041
legendary champions from just
champions or excellent players,

00:43:04.267 --> 00:43:10.491
and there are different categories,
as I say all the others and legends,

00:43:15.952 --> 00:43:20.140
is simply that you win one
more point than your opponent.

00:43:20.478 --> 00:43:25.278
You land one more shot,
make one better move,

00:43:25.580 --> 00:43:29.593
it doesn’t have to be six,
one is enough.

00:43:30.116 --> 00:43:40.541
But how, in what way,
that’s a broader story, long and wide,

00:43:41.251 --> 00:43:51.784
but the essence is that you need to
work mostly on your weaknesses,

00:43:52.220 --> 00:43:58.820
flaws and strengths,
not on how you’ll beat someone.

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:02.380
Of course you think about that,

00:44:02.580 --> 00:44:07.900
you adjust your game to his flaws,
to him, or to a team,

00:44:09.620 --> 00:44:14.900
but primarily it’s about you
as a tennis player, as a person,

00:44:15.100 --> 00:44:19.565
who you are when you
step on the court.

00:44:19.751 --> 00:44:21.871
Nadal and Federer have also
talked about it.

00:44:22.016 --> 00:44:23.994
Nadal, several times.

00:44:25.408 --> 00:44:30.488
He feels, when he steps on court,
and I’ve talked about it too,

00:44:30.795 --> 00:44:34.330
that we’ve already won
more than half the matches

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:36.980
before even playing a point.

00:44:37.220 --> 00:44:40.580
Because you see it
in your opponent’s eyes.

00:44:40.820 --> 00:44:44.460
You see the way they walk,
how they step on the court

00:44:44.604 --> 00:44:51.204
in front of 20,000 people
and how they handle it all.

00:44:53.316 --> 00:44:58.321
What’s very frustrating
for most players

00:44:58.780 --> 00:45:02.820
is when your whole résumé
and biography

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:09.140
starts getting read on court.
In tennis, that’s the culture.

00:45:10.020 --> 00:45:14.180
At Wimbledon they don’t do it,
but at other big tournaments,

00:45:14.460 --> 00:45:18.900
before you enter, they announce you.
And then on court,

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:22.860
they read everything you’ve won
and how many times.

00:45:23.100 --> 00:45:28.427
And while they read that,
you feel the energy from the crowd...

00:45:28.593 --> 00:45:30.745
It’s like in boxing:
"In the right corner is..."

00:45:31.101 --> 00:45:34.974
...you feel the charge,
and just imagine

00:45:35.094 --> 00:45:37.894
how it feels for your opponent
hearing all that.

00:45:38.203 --> 00:45:40.670
He has to warm up,
but his hand is shaking.

00:45:40.884 --> 00:45:44.920
That moment,
you must take advantage of it.

00:45:46.376 --> 00:45:50.349
That’s something I had to
battle with for years.

00:45:50.546 --> 00:45:53.685
I had to get used to them reading
all that about Federer and Nadal

00:45:53.764 --> 00:45:56.924
when I played against them...
-Yes, you mentioned those two years.

00:45:57.337 --> 00:46:01.977
Now, thank God,
the situation is reversed.

00:46:03.660 --> 00:46:05.727
But those are the moments

00:46:05.806 --> 00:46:07.886
I was talking about,
when everything matters.

00:46:07.969 --> 00:46:09.809
It’s important to
understand the stadium.

00:46:09.930 --> 00:46:14.087
To understand the wind direction.
To understand the smells.

00:46:14.265 --> 00:46:16.665
To know where you’re sitting.

00:46:16.819 --> 00:46:19.876
To know where your team is,
everything matters.

00:46:20.102 --> 00:46:26.477
You can’t act like you fell from the sky.
"I fell from Mars, but I’ll manage."

00:46:26.762 --> 00:46:31.126
There are some unforeseen situations
you have to adapt to,

00:46:31.318 --> 00:46:34.718
but you have to be ready,
man, this is your job.

00:46:34.879 --> 00:46:39.599
A man doesn’t come to an office,
to give a presentation,

00:46:39.834 --> 00:46:42.554
and only then decide
what he’ll talk about.

00:46:42.684 --> 00:46:46.907
You need some foundation,
your framework,

00:46:47.055 --> 00:46:49.884
prepared with your team.

00:46:50.379 --> 00:46:53.059
Someone comes in for
the presentation on screen,

00:46:53.337 --> 00:46:56.617
then later you enter into
a spontaneous conversation.

00:46:56.887 --> 00:46:59.527
But that’s how it goes.
Same in sports.

00:46:59.734 --> 00:47:04.974
You prepare your tactics, technique,
tighten all the screws,

00:47:05.340 --> 00:47:09.140
then you go out
and adjust to those things.

00:47:09.420 --> 00:47:14.540
But in your head, you already have,
so to speak, in your notebook:

00:47:15.123 --> 00:47:17.883
"I’m playing at Roland Garros,
if it’s a certain time,

00:47:18.089 --> 00:47:21.289
the sun’s in this position..."

00:47:21.468 --> 00:47:27.228
When I toss the ball, as we say,
like on a clock, from 1 to 12,

00:47:27.585 --> 00:47:32.599
if I toss it at 1, I get half the sun
in my eyes or all of it.

00:47:32.997 --> 00:47:37.380
But if I toss to the right,
everything’s clear, I can see.

00:47:37.580 --> 00:47:43.300
From this side, I’m playing
against the wind.

00:47:43.541 --> 00:47:45.919
Playing against a lefty.

00:47:46.060 --> 00:47:49.085
But if I toss to the right,
that automatically means

00:47:49.223 --> 00:47:51.773
he’ll move to the right side
because from there

00:47:51.915 --> 00:47:54.654
I don’t have the angle
to go down the center,

00:47:54.769 --> 00:47:57.209
I have to slice,
he reads that serve

00:47:57.410 --> 00:47:59.930
and most likely plays crosscourt...

00:48:00.138 --> 00:48:03.623
So you have a whole scenario
in your head.

00:48:03.938 --> 00:48:08.109
If I do this or that,
or toss here or there...?

00:48:08.540 --> 00:48:14.140
You kind of go crazy
from all this info, you know?

00:48:14.740 --> 00:48:18.620
But as an individual athlete,
you need that in your head.

00:48:19.060 --> 00:48:22.460
At least I do,
maybe others don’t.

00:48:23.220 --> 00:48:26.220
I feel I have to predict things
in my head,

00:48:26.302 --> 00:48:27.942
and then we’ll see what happens.

00:48:28.060 --> 00:48:31.820
As a coach, I’m interested in
form timing.

00:48:32.740 --> 00:48:36.820
How can you peak in tennis
without losing results?

00:48:37.100 --> 00:48:40.940
You mentioned Olympic sports
earlier and I get that.

00:48:41.260 --> 00:48:44.940
Something happens every 2 years
or a few times a year.

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:49.900
But in tennis-like in football-
you must peak each week.

00:48:50.220 --> 00:48:54.100
And in football it’s clearer,
in team sports,

00:48:55.780 --> 00:48:59.620
team form is the sum
of individual forms.

00:48:59.820 --> 00:49:02.700
The more players are in form,
the better the play,

00:49:02.900 --> 00:49:04.540
confidence grows.

00:49:04.740 --> 00:49:09.700
Then results come, and those
out of form improve too.

00:49:09.900 --> 00:49:13.620
You can push someone, rest them,
someone else steps in...

00:49:13.860 --> 00:49:18.420
But how do you time your form
when in January it’s Australia,

00:49:18.660 --> 00:49:22.660
in May Paris, July Wimbledon,
then September...

00:49:22.860 --> 00:49:26.020
And in between, a bunch of
important tournaments.

00:49:26.220 --> 00:49:30.780
Well, there are ways-you know,
that’s our sport’s nature.

00:49:30.980 --> 00:49:34.020
The schedule’s like that,
you must adapt.

00:49:34.102 --> 00:49:38.246
For most of your career,
when you’re young,

00:49:38.345 --> 00:49:40.205
every tournament matters.

00:49:40.578 --> 00:49:42.738
But these are the big ones,
we know that.

00:49:43.525 --> 00:49:45.525
Not everyone sees it that way.

00:49:45.726 --> 00:49:48.416
Many say Grand Slams
are the most important.

00:49:48.597 --> 00:49:54.107
Slams are their dream. But really,
they don’t live and train

00:49:54.388 --> 00:49:59.696
or plan their schedule
to peak for Grand Slams,

00:49:59.891 --> 00:50:02.987
to be freshest for those events.

00:50:03.489 --> 00:50:06.318
They don’t do it.
Most just don’t.

00:50:06.826 --> 00:50:10.060
Why? Because that’s how it is.

00:50:10.301 --> 00:50:13.684
Maybe they don’t believe
in themselves enough,

00:50:13.827 --> 00:50:16.067
don’t believe they
can go far in a Slam.

00:50:16.284 --> 00:50:21.255
So the week before, they try
to get some points elsewhere.

00:50:22.420 --> 00:50:26.260
You know, not everyone’s made
to compete at the top,

00:50:26.500 --> 00:50:30.700
for the biggest titles,
and that’s okay.

00:50:31.860 --> 00:50:34.460
But there are ways.

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:38.300
Federer helped me a lot with that,
not directly, but indirectly.

00:50:39.260 --> 00:50:43.060
I watched how he planned
his schedule.

00:50:43.500 --> 00:50:46.260
I learned a lot from him
in that sense.

00:50:47.100 --> 00:50:50.180
It helped me understand
how to time my form,

00:50:50.420 --> 00:50:54.780
when to take a break even
if I didn’t feel like it.

00:50:54.980 --> 00:50:59.660
I made mistakes too, didn’t
take breaks when I should’ve,

00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:04.220
but most of the time,
I made the right calls

00:51:04.420 --> 00:51:08.100
which helped me to win
and do what I’ve done.

00:51:08.340 --> 00:51:11.980
So I think you should always
keep an open mind and watch,

00:51:12.157 --> 00:51:14.668
because you never know who
you might learn from.

00:51:14.844 --> 00:51:19.418
Ivan Ljubičić, for example,
shared coach Riccardo Piatti

00:51:19.620 --> 00:51:23.340
with me when I was young,
17, 18 years old.

00:51:23.580 --> 00:51:29.180
Ivan helped me,
not just with my game,

00:51:29.780 --> 00:51:36.132
but with crucial details,
like what strings to use.

00:51:36.483 --> 00:51:44.995
What string pattern, vertical,
horizontal, racquet type...

00:51:45.189 --> 00:51:48.149
Back then, I was still thinking
whether to stick

00:51:48.420 --> 00:51:54.167
with my racquet or not, synthetic
or natural gut, or mix them.

00:51:54.261 --> 00:51:56.581
There are millions
of string combos.

00:51:56.680 --> 00:51:58.880
I listened to him-why?

00:51:59.012 --> 00:52:01.925
He was #3 in the world,
he knew what he was doing.

00:52:02.072 --> 00:52:03.712
And I trusted him.

00:52:04.055 --> 00:52:08.160
Like I said, I shared a coach
with him,

00:52:08.300 --> 00:52:10.932
we trained and traveled
together a lot.

00:52:11.074 --> 00:52:16.792
I’m grateful he was open with me,
that he shared those things,

00:52:16.968 --> 00:52:20.768
because he didn’t have to. Really,
he didn’t have to, and most don’t.

00:52:21.008 --> 00:52:25.949
We’re competitors, rivals.

00:52:27.003 --> 00:52:33.456
You’re young now, but tomorrow
we might fight for the same food.

00:52:34.540 --> 00:52:39.500
That’s why you have to be honest,
curious and ask tough questions,

00:52:39.700 --> 00:52:43.580
because how else will you know,
if you don’t ask?

00:52:44.020 --> 00:52:50.414
I always tried. Now, looking back,
sometimes I feel embarrassed

00:52:50.558 --> 00:52:53.734
about how I approached Goran
and gave him a Bonžita bar...

00:52:55.831 --> 00:52:58.984
"Who asks, doesn’t stray!"

00:52:59.332 --> 00:53:02.539
It’s better to ask and maybe
embarrass yourself than be silent.

00:53:02.652 --> 00:53:06.085
At least you’ll get an answer,
even if it’s a simple one.

00:53:06.474 --> 00:53:09.218
I’ll ask two more questions...

00:53:11.651 --> 00:53:14.835
You’re a citizen of the world.
A proud Serb,

00:53:14.980 --> 00:53:17.540
with Montenegrin
and Croatian roots.

00:53:17.907 --> 00:53:23.987
Do people from this region
have something special?

00:53:24.218 --> 00:53:31.945
If you think so, what is it?
Or are we just imagining it?

00:53:33.405 --> 00:53:44.201
I firmly believe we’re special.
-Special for what? -For many things.

00:53:44.845 --> 00:53:52.725
Look through history,
many minds came from here.

00:53:53.740 --> 00:54:03.219
In science, history, literature,
sports and arts...

00:54:04.940 --> 00:54:09.500
We all talk about it,
but it really is true.

00:54:10.860 --> 00:54:17.420
Maybe not to the same extent
as China in the IT sector,

00:54:17.620 --> 00:54:23.180
in Silicon Valley, but many of ours
have reached great heights

00:54:23.460 --> 00:54:32.500
thanks to engineering genes,
like Nikola Tesla’s.

00:54:34.700 --> 00:54:38.460
And because of those genes
and adaptability,

00:54:38.740 --> 00:54:44.500
thanks to intellect, they’ve succeeded
in that sphere worldwide.

00:54:44.740 --> 00:54:50.225
And proportionally, there are many,
given our population size.

00:54:50.347 --> 00:54:54.118
Compared to China or other
nations with billions of people.

00:54:54.660 --> 00:55:04.340
In that context, I don’t think
it’s a delusion.

00:55:05.100 --> 00:55:08.954
It’s not made up.
It really is true.

00:55:09.129 --> 00:55:11.929
And I’m proud of that, truly.

00:55:13.606 --> 00:55:19.312
That gives us confidence,
so when you go abroad,

00:55:19.477 --> 00:55:21.976
you know how to carry yourself.

00:55:23.260 --> 00:55:28.362
Thank God, I have lots of life
experience and I’ve met people

00:55:29.807 --> 00:55:34.380
from hospitality, real estate,
hotel management…

00:55:34.620 --> 00:55:41.940
Our people I’ve met around the world
these past twenty-something years,

00:55:42.580 --> 00:55:45.223
who shared stories with me.

00:55:45.440 --> 00:55:53.301
They leave with 100 dollars
in their pocket, to America,

00:55:54.140 --> 00:55:58.580
and they have to build a life there.

00:55:58.820 --> 00:56:02.540
They end up building empires
of restaurants and hotels.

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:08.340
They become multimillionaires.
These are inspiring stories.

00:56:09.180 --> 00:56:20.780
However, what’s negative,
probably for all in this region,

00:56:22.300 --> 00:56:27.060
and what creates a huge problem,

00:56:28.300 --> 00:56:36.060
though I don’t think it’s unfixable,
is the fact that we’re divided.

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:42.180
Until the moment the cup overflows.

00:56:42.540 --> 00:56:47.340
When there’s a crisis, we unite.
But why only then?

00:56:47.580 --> 00:56:53.540
Why can’t we be more constructive
with each other?

00:56:53.780 --> 00:56:56.220
We shouldn’t be fighting at home,

00:56:56.540 --> 00:57:00.900
while fighting out in the world
to prove ourselves.

00:57:01.180 --> 00:57:07.580
I won’t get into the topic of wars.
Those are wounds.

00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:15.186
I get that every side has its story,
its losses, and it’s hard.

00:57:15.405 --> 00:57:21.685
And sport is one of the areas,
one of the fields in society,

00:57:21.879 --> 00:57:25.880
that sends a message of unity
and normalizing relations.

00:57:25.975 --> 00:57:30.556
And it helps heal wounds, yes.
But those who’ve felt it...

00:57:30.876 --> 00:57:35.294
You can’t forget that.
And you shouldn’t.

00:57:35.786 --> 00:57:40.275
Some people can’t move past it.
I get that, and I respect that.

00:57:40.620 --> 00:57:47.290
But let’s at least try,
like neighbors, just a little.

00:57:47.626 --> 00:57:51.861
Like in business, let’s help
each other even a little,

00:57:52.103 --> 00:57:55.142
toward a more normal
and better life together.

00:57:55.368 --> 00:58:02.525
Because Serbia’s closest neighbor
is Croatia, and vice versa.

00:58:02.615 --> 00:58:09.415
Bosnia and Herzegovina, Macedonia…
It can’t be Spain, you get it?

00:58:09.980 --> 00:58:17.936
And in that sense, there’s this
bitter taste in my mouth.

00:58:18.300 --> 00:58:25.260
Because we’re so divided,
so resentful to each other.

00:58:25.500 --> 00:58:30.140
And in the end, we only work
against ourselves.

00:58:30.980 --> 00:58:34.331
Not just between nations,
but inside our own too.

00:58:34.558 --> 00:58:37.798
I see what we do
to each other in Serbia.

00:58:38.051 --> 00:58:42.190
I don’t believe it’s different
in Croatia or elsewhere.

00:58:42.500 --> 00:58:45.580
There’s a lot of inner division.

00:58:45.741 --> 00:58:50.421
But I still understand it,
because this region has suffered

00:58:50.724 --> 00:58:54.844
not just in a hundred years,
but in a thousand,

00:58:55.420 --> 00:59:02.126
even two thousand years.
The Ottomans were here...

00:59:02.445 --> 00:59:07.605
Conquerors of Europe from Asia
had to pass through here.

00:59:08.220 --> 00:59:12.620
We are a very proud people.

00:59:14.860 --> 00:59:20.220
And I’m proud we stand our ground,
that we don’t back down.

00:59:21.540 --> 00:59:32.205
But all of us would live easier
if we just eased up a little…

00:59:32.783 --> 00:59:38.879
If we made life more pleasant
for one another. -That’s true, Novak.

00:59:40.980 --> 00:59:45.780
This is a show for children,
and you’re a great humanitarian.

00:59:46.420 --> 00:59:51.900
Your wife Jelena runs an organization
that, through sports and workshops,

00:59:52.180 --> 00:59:55.940
tries to help children and parents
with advice drawn

00:59:56.380 --> 01:00:02.340
from your family’s experience
to help guide them on how to handle

01:00:02.700 --> 01:00:06.820
dreams, plans, expectations, all that.

01:00:10.460 --> 01:00:12.667
I’ve asked everyone,
so I’ll ask you too.

01:00:12.805 --> 01:00:16.800
How do you see the relationship
between talent and hard work

01:00:16.900 --> 01:00:19.002
in becoming a top athlete?

01:00:23.700 --> 01:00:26.660
Do you want a percentage
or just in general?

01:00:27.020 --> 01:00:30.500
How much is talent,
and how much is work?

01:00:30.780 --> 01:00:34.860
Of course, you can’t make it
just through talent or just work.

01:00:35.100 --> 01:00:39.940
In the past, work was
underrated. -Right.

01:00:40.180 --> 01:00:43.660
Now it seems that,
especially in elite sports,

01:00:43.783 --> 01:00:46.583
talent is the one being underestimated.

01:00:46.677 --> 01:00:50.331
There’s this idea in society that
"everyone can do everything." -True.

01:00:50.424 --> 01:00:52.304
But not everyone can do everything.

01:00:52.457 --> 01:00:55.217
I don’t mean that negatively,
but why force something,

01:00:55.348 --> 01:00:59.323
when maybe you’re meant for
something else? -I completely agree.

01:00:59.561 --> 01:01:02.361
Otherwise, we create trauma
and frustration.

01:01:03.198 --> 01:01:10.140
People say today that Ronaldo achieved
everything through hard work,

01:01:10.380 --> 01:01:13.860
that he has no talent. How can that be?
Of course he has talent.

01:01:14.061 --> 01:01:16.461
What’s your view on that balance?

01:01:16.609 --> 01:01:22.609
Ivanišević once said about you.
He’s never seen a player who,

01:01:23.020 --> 01:01:30.420
after 2–3 months off, comes back on court
and, within minutes, has an incredible

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:40.980
feel for space, the ball, the court, timing,
everything. That’s pure talent. -It is.

01:01:41.700 --> 01:01:43.860
I agree with your point.

01:01:44.060 --> 01:01:54.860
Right now, society is obsessed
with "work, work, work."

01:01:55.220 --> 01:02:03.740
That is essential, in everything,
especially in elite sport,

01:02:04.460 --> 01:02:10.587
it’s non-negotiable,
talent must be there...

01:02:11.620 --> 01:02:19.940
If work has replaced what used to be talent,
and if talent used to be the main factor,

01:02:20.140 --> 01:02:22.820
now it’s work. That’s the core shift.

01:02:23.020 --> 01:02:28.380
Talent is a God-given gift.

01:02:29.380 --> 01:02:37.660
It appears in childhood
and is shaped as you grow.

01:02:38.260 --> 01:02:48.180
One good thing about this region
is kids try different sports.

01:02:49.340 --> 01:02:54.620
Croatia and Serbia
are team-sport nations:

01:02:55.900 --> 01:03:02.620
basketball, water polo,
volleyball, handball, football.

01:03:03.020 --> 01:03:06.980
Tennis doesn’t have the same tradition
or cultural weight here.

01:03:07.220 --> 01:03:11.700
In Croatia, maybe a bit more.
But in Serbia, not really.

01:03:12.340 --> 01:03:17.634
You grow up trying different sports,
whatever’s available to you.

01:03:17.869 --> 01:03:20.589
Everyone has different circumstances.

01:03:20.851 --> 01:03:28.689
With the help of parents or a coach,
someone might say:

01:03:29.533 --> 01:03:36.540
"This child is meant for this sport,
or this art, he has talent."

01:03:37.356 --> 01:03:43.076
He has that spark, that potential.
And you grab hold of that.

01:03:43.940 --> 01:03:52.860
There are people with less talent
who made up for it through hard work,

01:03:53.060 --> 01:03:57.500
and through dedication,
they reached great heights. That’s real.

01:03:57.940 --> 01:04:03.100
But I agree that talent is decisive.

01:04:03.300 --> 01:04:10.250
Talent brings beauty
to an athlete’s performance.

01:04:10.780 --> 01:04:17.940
That’s why they say Federer is
the embodiment of tennis,

01:04:19.260 --> 01:04:26.860
elegance, style, the ease in his game
and movement. It’s true. Perfection.

01:04:27.740 --> 01:04:35.540
And on top of that, he’s one of the most
successful players in history,

01:04:36.260 --> 01:04:41.180
which makes his career incredible.
Perfection, in that sense.

01:04:41.420 --> 01:04:44.660
But talent must be there,
no question.

01:04:44.860 --> 01:04:52.500
To what degree, people debate,
offering their own views.

01:04:52.740 --> 01:04:56.780
They say Novak is less talented
than Federer.

01:04:57.020 --> 01:05:02.380
That doesn’t mean I lack talent.
I clearly do, just less, obviously.

01:05:02.860 --> 01:05:07.780
But I have my own kind of talent,
one that works for me,

01:05:08.100 --> 01:05:13.500
that gave my game and career
what it needed, like his did for him.

01:05:13.740 --> 01:05:17.260
Everyone carries their
own "something" through life.

01:05:17.460 --> 01:05:20.900
Thank God our sports
and games are so diverse,

01:05:21.100 --> 01:05:23.220
so there’s space for different
kinds of talent.

01:05:23.460 --> 01:05:27.540
Bravo, Novak. Thank you
for everything. -Thank you.

01:05:28.380 --> 01:05:33.820
I’ve enjoyed this, and I’m sure
our viewers will too. -Thank you again.

01:05:34.840 --> 01:05:35.978
Thank you so much.
-Thank you.

